{"cursor":"8000","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n'Polyketide synthases' ('PKS's) are a family of multi-domain enzymes or enzyme\ncomplexes that produce polyketides, a large class of secondary metabolites, in\nbacteria, fungi, plants, and a few animal lineages. The biosyntheses of\npolyketides share striking similarities with fatty acid\nbiosynthesis. Khosla, C., R. S. Gokhale, J. R. Jacobsen, and D. E. Cane.\n1999. Tolerance and specificity of polyketide synthases. Annu. Rev. Biochem. 68:219-253 Jenke-\nKodama, H., A. Sandmann, R. Muller, and E. Dittmann. 2005. Evolutionary\nimplications of bacterial polyketide synthases. Molecular Biology and Evolution\n22:2027-2039.\n\nThe PKS genes for a certain polyketide are usually organized in one operon in\nbacteria and in gene clusters in eukaryotes.\n","linknr":289,"url":"Polyketide_synthase","recorded":1362483275,"links":16,"instances":["biochemistry","biology","molecule"],"pdf":[],"categories":["EC 6.4"],"headings":["Classification","Modules and domains","Stages","Pharmacological Relevance","Ecological Significance","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a8/Anthracycline_aglycone_biosyn1.png/400px-Anthracycline_aglycone_biosyn1.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf8/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["domain","biology"],["cofactor","biochemistry"],["water","molecule"]],"members":["cofactor","domain","water"],"related":["Protein_domain","Enzyme","Multiprotein_complex","Polyketide","Secondary_metabolites","Bacterium","Fungi","Plant","Animal","Biosynthesis","Fatty_acid","Operon","Gene_cluster","Eukaryote","A